@formerly_azrielle: The French Connection
Won 5 (five) Oscars:
Best Actor in a Leading Role, Best Director, Best Film Editing, Best Picture, Best Writing, Screenplay Based on Material from Another Medium, Best Writing, Screenplay Based on Material from Another Medium. PLUS another 15 wins

@twentyforty
I understood what Gene Hackman's character meant--that he was going to break the guy's legs by snapping them in half using the curb and gutter for leverage, and then stomp the bones until they were so broken and crushed that they would resemble oatmeal when he was through.  But it was an idle threat--he was just saying it to the guy--with a smile on his face the whole time--because the guy couldn't understand what Gene's character was saying.  It was Gene's character's way of saying to the French to "kiss off, I'll try not to let the door slam me in the butt on my way to the airport, you can keep your miserable damn country!"  Or at least that's what I got out of it.  Just didn't care for the graphic detail--even in jest--which, btw, pretty much sums up the personal character and "integrity" of the detective Gene was playing on screen...I HATED him, and by association, couldn't stand Gene Hackman either.

Also, the MPAA was known in the 60's and 70's for awarding Oscars to films that were "less than popular" with the audiences that watched them, so the number of awards a movie won was relatively meaningless as a determination of the enjoyability of a movie, and hence the "worthwhileness" of seeing it.
